"The Checklist Manifesto" by Atul Gawande

Telumire 18th January 2023 at 12:48am

In "The Checklist Manifesto," Atul Gawande provides several pieces of advice for the use of checklists in various industries:

  • Keep checklists simple and short: Gawande stresses the importance of creating checklists that are easy to understand and follow. This means that they should be concise, with no more than a few items per list.
  • Make checklists visual: Gawande suggests using visual cues, such as boxes to check off or color coding, to help people quickly understand the status of a checklist and what needs to be done next.
  • Train people properly: Gawande emphasizes that it's important to provide proper training on how to use checklists in order to ensure that they are used effectively.
  • Use checklists as a tool for communication: Gawande notes that checklists can serve as a way to improve communication among team members, allowing them to share information and work together more effectively.
  • Continuously improve checklists: Gawande suggests that checklists should be continuously reviewed and improved, to ensure that they remain effective and relevant.
  • Use checklists for high-consequence and high-complexity tasks: Gawande recommends using checklists for tasks with high stakes and complexity such as surgery, construction, and aviation, where errors can have serious consequences.
  • Make checklists mandatory: Gawande suggests that making checklists mandatory for certain tasks can help ensure that they are used consistently and correctly.

Checklists can be used to improve efficiency and safety by standardizing processes and procedures, reducing errors, and improving communication among team members. When used correctly, checklists can help ensure that all necessary steps are taken for a given task and that nothing is forgotten.

To create clear and simple checklists, it is important to:

  • Keep the number of items on the checklist to a minimum.
  • Use simple language that is easy to understand.
  • Use visual cues such as boxes to check off or color coding to help people quickly understand the status of the checklist and what needs to be done next.

To ensure the effectiveness of checklists, it is important to:

  • Provide proper training on how to use the checklist.
  • Continuously review and improve the checklist to ensure that it remains relevant and effective.
  • Make the checklist mandatory for certain tasks, to ensure that it is used consistently and correctly.
  • Encourage open communication and a culture of continuous improvement, to facilitate the effective use of checklists.
  • Adapt the checklists to the specific needs of the organization.
  • Monitor and measure the results of using checklists, and make necessary adjustments.

It's also important to note that checklists are not a panacea and should be used in conjunction with other methodologies, and that checklists should be used for high-consequence and high-complexity tasks.

The book offers several additional insights and lessons beyond the use of checklists in various industries:

  • The importance of standardization: Gawande argues that standardization is key to reducing errors and improving efficiency in complex systems. He notes that checklists can be used to standardize processes and procedures, making it easier for people to work together effectively.
  • The role of culture in success: Gawande discusses how culture can play a role in the success of checklists, noting that a culture that values open communication and continuous improvement is more likely to be able to effectively implement and use checklists.
  • The power of small changes: Gawande shows how small changes, such as the use of a checklist, can have a big impact in improving safety and efficiency in high-stakes industries like healthcare and aviation.
  • The challenge of human fallibility: Gawande acknowledges that human fallibility is a major challenge in complex systems, and notes that checklists can be an effective tool to help mitigate this challenge.
  • The value of simplicity: Gawande emphasizes the value of simplicity in creating effective checklists, noting that simple checklists are more likely to be followed and to be effective in reducing errors.
  • The importance of proper implementation: Gawande notes that for checklists to be effective, they must be implemented properly, with proper training and resources.
  • The need for continuous improvement: Gawande stresses that checklists should be continuously reviewed and improved to make sure they are effective and relevant, and that they should be adapted to the specific needs of the organization.

On New Year's Eve (by the way, try to search this on google for a surprise!), I battle-tested chatGPT in an impromptu tabletop game with my friends.. At first, it was shockingly good, but as the game went on, we noticed that the AI struggled with originality and sometimes got stuck in repetitive responses. . Despite this, it was able to generate coherent answers and added some level of enjoyment to the game. One prompt that seemed to work particularly well was:

I want you to act like you are simulating a Multi-User Dungeon (MUD). Subsequent commands should be interpreted as being sent to the MUD. The MUD should allow me to navigate the world, interact with the world, observe the world, and interact with both NPCs and (simulated) player characters. I should be able to pick up objects, use objects, carry an inventory, and also say arbitrary things to any other players. You should simulate the occasional player character coming through, as though this was a person connected online. There should be a goal and a purpose to the MUD. The storyline of the MUD should be affected by my actions but can also progress on its own in between commands. I can also type “.” if I just want the simulated MUD to progress further without without any actions. The MUD should offer a list of commands that can be viewed via ‘help’. Before we begin, please just acknowledge you understand the request and then I will send one more message describing the environment for the MUD (the context, plot, character I am playing, etc.) After that, please respond by simulating the spawn-in event in the MUD for the player.

Prompt by https://youtube.com/@ItsJetsnipe

I think it can be quite useful for preparing games however.

    Ditching the mouse: How to navigate using a keyboard

    Telumire 28th January 2023 at 10:58am

    My PC bt is increasingly instable as the years come and goes, and I reached a point where I want to ditch my bluetooth mouse entirely, whenever possible.

    As a front end web dev, forcing me to use the keyboard to navigate is also an opportunity to understand assistive technologies better.

    Firefox:

    Command Shortcut
    Back alt + ←
    Forward alt + →
    Home Alt + Home
    Open File Ctrl + O
    Reload F5 / Ctrl + R
    Reload (override cache) Ctrl + F5 / Ctrl + Shift + R
    Stop Esc
    Current Page
    Focus Next Tab
    Focus Previous Shift + Tab
    Go Down a Screen Page Down / Space bar
    Go Up a Screen Page Up / Shift + Space bar
    Go to Bottom of Page End / Ctrl + ↓
    Go to Top of Page Home / Ctrl + ↑
    Next Frame, Pop-Up F6
    Previous Frame, Pop-Up Shift + F6
    Print Ctrl + P
    Save Focused Link (browser.altClickSave = true) Alt + Enter
    Save Page As Ctrl + S
    Zoom In Ctrl + +
    Zoom Out Ctrl + -
    Zoom Reset Ctrl + 0
    Editing
    Copy Ctrl + C
    Cut Ctrl + X
    Delete Del
    Delete Word to the Left Ctrl + Backspace
    Delete Word to the Right Ctrl + Del
    Go one Word to the Left Ctrl + ←
    Go one Word to the Right Ctrl + →
    Go to Beginning of Line Home / Ctrl + ↑
    Go to End of Line End / Ctrl + ↓
    Go to Beginning of Text Ctrl + Home
    Go to End of Text Ctrl + End
    Paste Ctrl + V
    Paste (as plain text) Ctrl + Shift + V
    Redo Ctrl + Y / Ctrl + Shift + Z
    Select All Ctrl + A
    Undo Ctrl + Z

    Source:

    • https://firefox-source-docs.mozilla.org/devtools-user/keyboard_shortcuts/index.html
    • https://support.mozilla.org/en-US/kb/keyboard-shortcuts-perform-firefox-tasks-quickly

    Identifying Your Struggles: Understanding Your Motivation and Productivity Challenges

    Telumire 18th January 2023 at 1:59am

    Introduction:

    One of the first steps in achieving your goals and changing your habits is to understand the underlying causes of your motivation and productivity challenges. Whether it's procrastination, negative thoughts and emotions, or simply a lack of motivation, understanding the root of these struggles is crucial to finding effective solutions.

    Self-Awareness and Self-Reflection:

    One of the most important tools for identifying your struggles is self-awareness and self-reflection. This involves taking the time to observe your thoughts, emotions, and behaviors, and to identify patterns and triggers that may be contributing to your struggles. For example, if you find yourself procrastinating on a regular basis, you may want to ask yourself what is causing this behavior and what you gain from it.

    Common Obstacles:

    Procrastination, negative thoughts, and emotions, and lack of motivation are some of the most common obstacles that people face when trying to change their habits and achieve their goals. To overcome these obstacles, it is important to understand the underlying causes and to develop strategies for addressing them.

    For example, procrastination is often caused by a lack of motivation, a fear of failure, or a lack of clarity about the task at hand. To overcome procrastination, it can be helpful to set clear and specific goals, to break tasks down into smaller, more manageable steps, and to reward yourself for making progress.

    Negative thoughts and emotions can also be a major obstacle to motivation and productivity. To overcome these thoughts and emotions, it can be helpful to practice mindfulness, to challenge negative thought patterns, and to develop coping strategies for dealing with difficult emotions.

    The Science Behind Motivation and Productivity:

    The psychological and neuroscientific factors that contribute to motivation and productivity are complex and multifaceted. Research has shown that motivation is influenced by a variety of factors, including our thoughts, emotions, and beliefs, as well as the way that we perceive and interact with our environment.

    One of the key concepts in understanding motivation is the idea of self-regulation, which refers to the ability to control our thoughts, emotions, and behaviors in order to achieve our goals. Research has shown that self-regulation is a key predictor of motivation and productivity, and that people who are able to regulate their thoughts and emotions are more likely to achieve their goals.

    Another important concept in understanding motivation is the idea of goal-setting, which refers to the process of setting specific and measurable objectives for oneself. Research has shown that setting specific and challenging goals is associated with higher levels of motivation and productivity, and that people who set goals for themselves are more likely to achieve them.

    Conclusion:

    In order to change your habits and achieve your goals, it is essential to understand the underlying causes of your motivation and productivity challenges. By developing self-awareness and self-reflection, identifying common obstacles, and understanding the psychological and neuroscientific factors that contribute to motivation and productivity, you can develop strategies and techniques that will help you to overcome these challenges and to achieve your goals.

    Changing Your Mindset: Overcoming Negative Thoughts and Emotions

    Overcoming negative thoughts and emotions is a crucial step in understanding and addressing motivation and productivity challenges. Negative thoughts, such as self-doubt, fear of failure, and perfectionism, can lead to procrastination, lack of motivation, and ultimately, decreased productivity.

    One effective strategy for changing your mindset is to challenge negative thoughts through cognitive-behavioral techniques such as cognitive restructuring. This involves identifying and questioning the assumptions and beliefs that underlie negative thoughts, and replacing them with more balanced and realistic perspectives.

    For example, if you find yourself thinking "I can't do this, it's too hard," you can challenge this thought by asking yourself: "What is the evidence for and against this thought? Are there other ways of looking at this situation?" This can help to shift your perspective and reduce feelings of helplessness and hopelessness.

    Another effective strategy is to practice mindfulness and acceptance. This involves learning to observe and accept negative thoughts and emotions without getting caught up in them. Mindfulness practices such as meditation and yoga can help to increase awareness and decrease reactivity to negative thoughts and emotions.

    Lastly, finding healthy ways to express and cope with negative emotions can also help to change your mindset. This can include talking to a therapist or counselor, journaling, or engaging in activities that promote emotional regulation such as art, music, or exercise.

    It's important to remember that changing your mindset and overcoming negative thoughts and emotions is not a one-time event, but rather a continuous process that requires patience, practice, and self-compassion.

    In conclusion, understanding and addressing the underlying causes of motivation and productivity challenges is key in achieving goals and reaching a sense of fulfillment. Identifying the factors that hold us back and learning effective strategies to change our mindset can lead to a more positive and productive life.

    Introduction: Understanding the Science of Changing Habits

    Telumire 18th January 2023 at 1:49am

    In this chapter, we will provide an overview of the latest scientific research on motivation, habit formation, and behavior change. We will explore the key concepts and theories that underpin our understanding of how and why people change their habits, and what factors influence the success or failure of habit change efforts.

    We will discuss the important role that neuroscience plays in understanding habit formation, including the neural mechanisms that underlie habit formation and the ways in which different regions of the brain interact to regulate motivation and behavior.

    We will also explore the role of psychology and behavior economics in habit change, including the influence of cognitive biases, self-regulation, and decision-making on habit formation.

    Finally, we will introduce key strategies and techniques for changing habits and achieving goals, including goal-setting, self-monitoring, and creating a supportive environment for habit change.

    Overall, this chapter will provide a foundational understanding of the science of changing habits and set the stage for the rest of the book.

    Motivation, habit formation, and behavior change are complex processes that have been studied extensively in the field of psychology and neuroscience. Recent research has provided valuable insights into the underlying mechanisms and factors that influence these processes, and has led to the development of effective strategies and techniques for changing habits and achieving goals.

    One key concept in the science of habit formation is the idea of "cue-routine-reward" loop, where a specific cue or trigger leads to a specific routine or behavior, which in turn leads to a reward or positive outcome. This loop can become ingrained in our brains, leading to the formation of habits. Research has shown that by identifying and altering the cues and rewards associated with a specific habit, it is possible to change the behavior.

    Another important aspect of habit formation is the role of willpower and self-regulation. Willpower can be thought of as a limited resource that can be depleted through overuse, making it harder to resist temptations and maintain a desired behavior. Self-regulation strategies, such as goal-setting, self-monitoring, and creating a supportive environment can help to conserve willpower and make it easier to maintain desired behaviors.

    In terms of neuroscience, recent research has shown that habit formation is associated with changes in the brain, specifically in the striatum and prefrontal cortex regions. These changes occur in the form of changes in the strength of connections between neurons, a process known as synaptic plasticity. This is a process that happen also in other brain regions that are involved in motivation, emotion, and decision making.

    In addition to these specific strategies, research has shown that mindfulness practices, such as meditation and yoga, can also be effective in promoting self-regulation and changing habits.

    Overall, the latest scientific research on motivation, habit formation, and behavior change provides valuable insights into the underlying mechanisms and factors that influence these processes. By understanding these concepts and utilizing effective strategies and techniques, it is possible to change habits and achieve goals.

    Implementing Change: Techniques and Strategies for Modifying Habits

    One of the key concepts in understanding habit change is the idea of cues and rewards. A cue is a trigger that initiates a behavior, while a reward is the positive outcome that reinforces the behavior. In order to change a habit, it is essential to identify the specific cue and reward associated with the habit, and then alter or replace them.

    For example, imagine that you want to change the habit of snacking on junk food during the afternoon at work. The cue for this habit might be feeling bored or stressed during the workday, and the reward might be the temporary pleasure of eating something sweet or salty. To change this habit, you could try to identify alternative activities that can provide a similar reward, such as taking a walk outside, calling a friend, or reading a book. You can also try to change the cue by planning ahead and bringing healthy snacks to work.

    Self-monitoring and goal-setting are also important tools in changing habits. Self-monitoring involves keeping track of your progress, such as by keeping a journal of your habits or using an app to track your progress. Goal-setting involves setting specific, measurable, and realistic goals for yourself, such as aiming to eat a certain number of fruits and vegetables per day.

    Creating a supportive environment is also crucial in changing habits. This includes surrounding yourself with people who support your goals, removing temptations from your environment, and finding ways to make healthy behaviors more convenient. For example, you can put healthy snacks in plain sight, and make it harder to access unhealthy foods.

    The science behind habit formation can help us to understand the processes that drive habit change. Research has shown that habits are formed in a specific part of the brain, the basal ganglia, which is responsible for automatic and unconscious behaviors. When we repeat a behavior, connections between neurons in the basal ganglia become stronger, making the behavior more automatic and difficult to change. However, by identifying and changing the cues and rewards associated with a habit, we can weaken these connections and create new habits.

    One of the most crucial steps in changing a habit is understanding the cues and rewards that are associated with it. Cues are the triggers that initiate a behavior, while rewards are the positive outcomes that reinforce it. In order to change a habit, it is essential to identify the cues and rewards associated with it and then modify them in a way that promotes the desired behavior.

    Self-monitoring is an important tool in this process. By keeping a log of your habits and the cues and rewards associated with them, you can begin to see patterns and identify areas that need to be changed. This can be done through a variety of methods, such as keeping a journal, using a habit-tracking app, or even simply observing yourself throughout the day.

    Once you have identified the cues and rewards associated with a habit, the next step is to change them. This can be done by altering the cues in a way that makes the desired behavior more likely, or by providing different rewards that reinforce the desired behavior. For example, if you are trying to break the habit of snacking on junk food in the evening, you might change the cue by moving the junk food out of sight, or by setting a specific time to have your snack. Alternatively, you might provide a different reward, such as a healthy snack or a relaxing activity, to reinforce the desired behavior.

    Creating a supportive environment is also key to changing habits. This includes both the physical environment and the people around you. For example, if you are trying to break the habit of procrastinating, you might create a dedicated workspace with minimal distractions, or set boundaries with friends and family who tend to distract you. Additionally, it can be helpful to surround yourself with people who are supportive of your goals and who can provide encouragement and accountability.

    The science behind habit formation is complex and multifaceted, but it is rooted in the brain. Research has shown that habits are formed and reinforced through a process called "habituation," which occurs in the basal ganglia, a region of the brain involved in movement and motivation. Habituation involves the formation of neural pathways that link cues and rewards together, making it easier to perform a behavior in the future.

    One way to change habits is by working with the brain's natural processes. For example, by identifying the specific cues and rewards associated with a habit, you can interrupt the neural pathways that have been formed. Additionally, by providing alternative rewards, you can create new neural pathways that promote the desired behavior.

    In summary, the key to changing habits is to understand the cues and rewards associated with them, and then modify them in a way that promotes the desired behavior. This can be done through self-monitoring, goal-setting, and creating a supportive environment. Additionally, by understanding the science behind habit formation, you can work with the brain's natural processes to change habits in a sustainable way.

    Les bases de l'optimisation CSS

    Telumire 17th November 2022 at 5:36pm

    Résumé du livre "CSS Optimization Basics" par Jens Oliver Meiert. Ce livre est open-source et peut être lu gratuitement sur github (en anglais) : https://github.com/j9t/css-optimization-basics

    voir aussi https://web.dev/fast/#optimize-your-css

    Le code présenté ici suit le guide de style HTML/CSS de google : https://google.github.io/styleguide/htmlcssguide.html

    Compréhension

    Pour être efficace, il faut s'assurer que le code reste compréhensible. Pour la cohérence, cela s'applique aussi au travail individuel : il faut au moins rester cohérent avec nous-mêmes.

    Cela peut être atteint via documentation et commentaires, mais plus important encore : trier les déclarations de façon cohérente.

    Cohérence

    Plusieur niveaux de cohérence:

    • Niveau 1 (individu) : écrire et formater les choses de façon prévisible pour nous-mêmes.
    • Niveau 2 (groupe) : doit être cohérent avec le style utilisé par d'autres.
    • Niveau 3 (institution) : suivre les standards d'une organisation.

    Être cohérent facilite grandement l'optimisation du code.

    Code sans cohérence.Ordre des déclarations et sélecteurs corrigé.
    .feeds ul,
.posts ul ,

  list-style: none;
  margin: 0

  border-top: 0;
  padding-top: 0;
}

.posts li:last-child,
.events li:last-child {
  padding-bottom: 0;
}

    css
    Note : la pseudo-class :is serait égallement un très bon choix pour simplifier un tel code.
    • Établir des lignes directrices pour le code
    • Utiliser ou créer des outils pour suivre et tester que les règles sont respectées

    La plupart des règles peuvent et seront appliquées au moment du codage, d'autres lors de la publication si l'on doit appliquer des règles légèrement différentes.

    Tris des déclarations (automatisable)

    Google recommande le tris alphabétique, sauf pour les préfix vendeurs, qui sont à déclarer juste avant leur déclaration principale.

    Cela permet de savoir ou chercher une propriété particulière rapidemment, tout en étant facile à mettre en oeuvre.

    Tris des sélecteurs

    Beaucoup plus difficile à mettre en oeuvre. L'une des seules tentatives : https://meiert.com/en/blog/how-to-order-css-selectors/

    Le tris des sélecteurs est crucial pour pouvoir suivre le principe DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself), qui aide la maintenance et réduit la complexité des tests.

    Une convention possible est de commencer par les éléments blocks de haut niveau, puis les éléments du niveau suivant, puis les classes et ID, etc.

    Simplicité

    Simplicité et minimalisme ne sont pas toujours corrélé, comme dans le cas des notations raccourcies (shorthands), mais elles le sont quand il s'agit de réduire le nombre de caractères.

    Un code simple est plus facile à comprendre et souvent plus rapide. Cela demande aussi un certain niveau de compétence.

    Nom des classes et ID

    Avec OOCSS, BEM, Atomic CSS, Tailwind, les conventions de nommages d'ID et de classes ne sont plus une préoccupation importante.

    Cependant, à l'échelle de plus petits projets, on ne bénéficie pas de schéma de nommage sacrifiant compréhension et maintenabilité pour de brève soupes de classe présentationnelle (Atomic CSS). Les ID tout comme les sélecteurs universel ont toujours leur place, ainsi que !important et les shorthands.

    Les régles de nommages pour ID et class sont simples et durables :

    • Garder l'utilisation des ID et classes à un minimum.
    • Si nécessaire, utiliser des ID et noms de classes fonctionnels, sinon utiliser des ID noms de classe générique.
    • Garder les noms le plus court possible mais aussi aussi long que nécessaire.

    Ces trois règles constituent un bon point de départ.

    Notations raccourcie

    Elles permettent d'écrire moins de code, mais peuvent être difficile à comprendre. Cela conduit certains à les qualifier d'"anti-pattern" tandis que d'autres ne sont pas de cet avis.

    Les deux camps ont raison. Elles pertmettent de réduire le code dans tout les cas, mais pour les projets complexes leurs implications peuvent conduire à des complications détrimentales, du fait de leurs valeurs implicites.

    Elles restent cependant très utiles pour des projets plus modestes.

    Performance

    Les performances de rendus ne sont pas aussi importantes que les performances de chargement.

    Par exemple, ne pas ommettre des tags optionnels pour éviter au navigateur de devoir les compléter est beaucoup moins important que d'optimiser des images. En pratique, ce genre de calculations est si rapide que l'impact est négligeable.

    Performances des sélecteurs

    Un article de Steve Souders montre que même des stylesheets avec 18000 règles sont rendues en environ 600ms.

    Pour la plupart des sites webs, les gains possibles seront négligeables et n'en valent pas le coût. Certaines règles CSS et interactions avec javascript peuvent rendre une page sensiblement plus lente - c'est là que des efforts devraient être faits.

    Les sélecteurs comme le sécteur universel ne méritent pas d'être bannis d'usage.Cependant, la méthodologie n'était pas sans problèmes et selon Ben Frain :

    Il est pratiquement impossible de prédire l'impact final sur les performances simplement en examinant les sélecteurs.

    https://benfrain.com/css-performance-revisited-selectors-bloat-expensive-styles/
    1. Optimiser les sélecteurs n'apporte pas de gains remarquables,
    2. Cela ralentit l'écriture du code et peut le rendre plus difficile à lire.

    CSS inline

    Éviter. Oui, cela peut améliorer les performances (réduit les requêtes HTTP, applique des sélecteurs plus rapidement), mais cela viole la séparation présentation/contenu et rend la maintenance trop difficile.

    L'exception étant pour des styles uniques pour des pages uniques. l'HTML doit être le plus dépouillé possible pour être le plus facile à maintenir.

    Les avancées récentes en gestion de contenu et process de déploiement rendent cependant la maintenance HTML bien plus facile, c'est donc un problème moins préoccupant de nos jours.

    Être prudent dans les déclarations

    Possiblement important.box-shadow, filter, opacity, et transform, selon leurs valeurs, peuvent être beaucoup plus lentes que d'autres. Il reste cependant difficile de prédire l'impact de ces règles, cela ne doit donc pas être une priorité.

    Hygiène des règles

    Supprimer le CSS inutilisé a un gros impact sur les performances, mais n'est pas évident à mettre en oeuvre. Quelques actions pouvant aider :

    • Utiliser des sections et commenter le code
    • Utiliser des sélecteurs descriptifs et au moins "direct" (footer plutôt que body>:last-child)
    • Suivre et supprimer le code inutilisé
    • Revoir régulièrement les feuilles de style
    • Utiliser des outils :
      • L'onglet "Coverage" des Chrome Developer Tools
      • Unused CSS crawler (le plus complet)
      • UnCSS online tool, script, et package
      • PurifyCSS script
      • PurgeCSS package
      • rm-unused-css package
      • ngx-unused-css package (pour Angular)

    Pour l'optimisation des images, voir https://images.guide/

    Qualité

    Validation

    Les tests permettent de vérifier que le code fonctionne, et la validation assure qu'il n'y'a pas d'erreurs.

    La validation joue un rôle critique pour s'assurer que le code est syntaxiquement correct. Les validateurs peuvent ne pas être au fait des dernières nouveautés mais cela ne doit pas nous empêcher de valider le code.

    https://jigsaw.w3.org/css-validator/, https://uitest.com/analysis/#conformance

    Maintenance

    Éviter le travail inutile. Utiliser des conventions de nommage correct pour le nom des feuilles de styles est un bon départ.

    !important

    Utile pour des tests rapide et pour débugger, pour des déclarations en début de code qui ne sont pas trop spécifiques et risquent d'être écrasées.

    Séparation des préoccupations

    Séparer structure (HTML), présentation (CSS) et fonctionnalités (Javascript). Cela assure que l'on utilise les bons outils, et permet de savoir ou chercher lorsque des problèmes arrivent.

    Dans les feuilles de styles, deux options :

    • Séparer les styles par fonctions et les décomposer en modules (BEM)
    • Ne rien faire de particulier, car si l'on trie les sélecteurs de façon cohérente, cela mène à un ordre modulaire. On peut DRY par module, mais aussi pour toute la feuille de style, ce que l'approche BEM rend difficile.

    DRY

    Limiter la répétition de déclarations, limiter le nombre d'endroits ou un style est définit.

    • Écrire le CSS
    • Décider les limites DRY : par sections (code CSS fonctionnel indépendant), fichier, composant, @media ?
    • Utiliser les mêmes formats pour faciliter la recherche de doublons (ex : background: none, background:none, et background-image: none)
    • Chercher les doublons :
      • Nouvelles feuilles de styels : aprés le setup initial
      • Ajouts et bug fixes : après le travail
      • Astuce: Si la colorisation de version control ne suffit pas, indenter temporairement les déclarations changées pour vérifier les répétitions seuls.
    • Supprimer les doublons :
      • Déterminez quelle règle respective doit venir en premier dans la feuille de style (pour cela, il faut avoir une norme non écrite ou écrite sur la façon d'ordonner les sélecteurs).
      • Si cette première règle contient des déclarations supplémentaires, c'est-à-dire des déclarations que nous n'avons pas encore vérifiées ou qui ne sont pas des doublons, copiez la règle entière et collez-la après l'original. Conservez le doublon découvert dans la première règle et supprimez les autres déclarations, et vice versa dans la deuxième règle, de sorte que cette dernière ressemble à l'ancienne règle, mais sans la déclaration que nous avons trouvée utilisée plus d'une fois.
      • Copiez les sélecteurs des autres règles qui contiennent la déclaration dupliquée respective dans la règle qui vient en premier.
      • Veillez à supprimer les déclarations dupliquées dont les sélecteurs viennent d'être copiés dans la feuille de style, et à supprimer la règle entière si elle ne contient que la déclaration dupliquée qui a été déplacée.
      • (Répétez.)
    • Vérifier que l'ordre des sélecteurs est correct.
    • .. ainsi que le placement des règles.
    • Répéter, tester.

    https://cssstats.com/ permet de voir le ratio des déclarations uniques dans une feuille de style

    Ces consignes permettent générallement de réduire le poids d'une feuille de style. Il est aussi possible de compresser les feuilles de style pour gagner encore en performances.

    Less known evidence-based strategies effective in increasing motivation and improving productivity

    Telumire 18th January 2023 at 1:11am
    • Use the Zeigarnik effect: This effect states that people tend to remember unfinished tasks better than completed ones. Leave a task unfinished can increase motivation to finish it.
    • Use the Self-Determination Theory: This theory posits that people are more motivated when they feel a sense of autonomy, competence and relatedness to their goals.
    • Use the Self-Concordance Model: This model states that people are more motivated to achieve goals that are congruent with their values, abilities, and goals.
    • Use the Self-Efficacy theory: This theory posits that people are more motivated when they believe they have the skills and abilities to achieve a goal.
    • Use the Flow theory: This theory posits that people are more motivated when they are fully engaged in an activity, and that it can help to increase motivation and productivity.

    Introduction: Understanding the Science of Changing Habits

    In this chapter, we will provide an overview of the latest scientific research on motivation, habit formation, and behavior change. We will explore the key concepts and theories that underpin our understanding of how and why people change their habits, and what factors influence the success or failure of habit change efforts.

    We will discuss the important role that neuroscience plays in understanding habit formation, including the neural mechanisms that underlie habit formation and the ways in which different regions of the brain interact to regulate motivation and behavior.

    We will also explore the role of psychology and behavior economics in habit change, including the influence of cognitive biases, self-regulation, and decision-making on habit formation.

    Finally, we will introduce key strategies and techniques for changing habits and achieving goals, including goal-setting, self-monitoring, and creating a supportive environment for habit change.

    Overall, this chapter will provide a foundational understanding of the science of changing habits and set the stage for the rest of the book.

    Motivation, habit formation, and behavior change are complex processes that have been studied extensively in the field of psychology and neuroscience. Recent research has provided valuable insights into the underlying mechanisms and factors that influence these processes, and has led to the development of effective strategies and techniques for changing habits and achieving goals.

    One key concept in the science of habit formation is the idea of "cue-routine-reward" loop, where a specific cue or trigger leads to a specific routine or behavior, which in turn leads to a reward or positive outcome. This loop can become ingrained in our brains, leading to the formation of habits. Research has shown that by identifying and altering the cues and rewards associated with a specific habit, it is possible to change the behavior.

    Another important aspect of habit formation is the role of willpower and self-regulation. Willpower can be thought of as a limited resource that can be depleted through overuse, making it harder to resist temptations and maintain a desired behavior. Self-regulation strategies, such as goal-setting, self-monitoring, and creating a supportive environment can help to conserve willpower and make it easier to maintain desired behaviors.

    In terms of neuroscience, recent research has shown that habit formation is associated with changes in the brain, specifically in the striatum and prefrontal cortex regions. These changes occur in the form of changes in the strength of connections between neurons, a process known as synaptic plasticity. This is a process that happen also in other brain regions that are involved in motivation, emotion, and decision making.

    In addition to these specific strategies, research has shown that mindfulness practices, such as meditation and yoga, can also be effective in promoting self-regulation and changing habits.

    Overall, the latest scientific research on motivation, habit formation, and behavior change provides valuable insights into the underlying mechanisms and factors that influence these processes. By understanding these concepts and utilizing effective strategies and techniques, it is possible to change habits and achieve goals.

    Implementing Change: Techniques and Strategies for Modifying Habits

    One of the key concepts in understanding habit change is the idea of cues and rewards. A cue is a trigger that initiates a behavior, while a reward is the positive outcome that reinforces the behavior. In order to change a habit, it is essential to identify the specific cue and reward associated with the habit, and then alter or replace them.

    For example, imagine that you want to change the habit of snacking on junk food during the afternoon at work. The cue for this habit might be feeling bored or stressed during the workday, and the reward might be the temporary pleasure of eating something sweet or salty. To change this habit, you could try to identify alternative activities that can provide a similar reward, such as taking a walk outside, calling a friend, or reading a book. You can also try to change the cue by planning ahead and bringing healthy snacks to work.

    Self-monitoring and goal-setting are also important tools in changing habits. Self-monitoring involves keeping track of your progress, such as by keeping a journal of your habits or using an app to track your progress. Goal-setting involves setting specific, measurable, and realistic goals for yourself, such as aiming to eat a certain number of fruits and vegetables per day.

    Creating a supportive environment is also crucial in changing habits. This includes surrounding yourself with people who support your goals, removing temptations from your environment, and finding ways to make healthy behaviors more convenient. For example, you can put healthy snacks in plain sight, and make it harder to access unhealthy foods.

    The science behind habit formation can help us to understand the processes that drive habit change. Research has shown that habits are formed in a specific part of the brain, the basal ganglia, which is responsible for automatic and unconscious behaviors. When we repeat a behavior, connections between neurons in the basal ganglia become stronger, making the behavior more automatic and difficult to change. However, by identifying and changing the cues and rewards associated with a habit, we can weaken these connections and create new habits.

    One of the most crucial steps in changing a habit is understanding the cues and rewards that are associated with it. Cues are the triggers that initiate a behavior, while rewards are the positive outcomes that reinforce it. In order to change a habit, it is essential to identify the cues and rewards associated with it and then modify them in a way that promotes the desired behavior.

    Self-monitoring is an important tool in this process. By keeping a log of your habits and the cues and rewards associated with them, you can begin to see patterns and identify areas that need to be changed. This can be done through a variety of methods, such as keeping a journal, using a habit-tracking app, or even simply observing yourself throughout the day.

    Once you have identified the cues and rewards associated with a habit, the next step is to change them. This can be done by altering the cues in a way that makes the desired behavior more likely, or by providing different rewards that reinforce the desired behavior. For example, if you are trying to break the habit of snacking on junk food in the evening, you might change the cue by moving the junk food out of sight, or by setting a specific time to have your snack. Alternatively, you might provide a different reward, such as a healthy snack or a relaxing activity, to reinforce the desired behavior.

    Creating a supportive environment is also key to changing habits. This includes both the physical environment and the people around you. For example, if you are trying to break the habit of procrastinating, you might create a dedicated workspace with minimal distractions, or set boundaries with friends and family who tend to distract you. Additionally, it can be helpful to surround yourself with people who are supportive of your goals and who can provide encouragement and accountability.

    The science behind habit formation is complex and multifaceted, but it is rooted in the brain. Research has shown that habits are formed and reinforced through a process called "habituation," which occurs in the basal ganglia, a region of the brain involved in movement and motivation. Habituation involves the formation of neural pathways that link cues and rewards together, making it easier to perform a behavior in the future.

    One way to change habits is by working with the brain's natural processes. For example, by identifying the specific cues and rewards associated with a habit, you can interrupt the neural pathways that have been formed. Additionally, by providing alternative rewards, you can create new neural pathways that promote the desired behavior.

    In summary, the key to changing habits is to understand the cues and rewards associated with them, and then modify them in a way that promotes the desired behavior. This can be done through self-monitoring, goal-setting, and creating a supportive environment. Additionally, by understanding the science behind habit formation, you can work with the brain's natural processes to change habits in a sustainable way.

    Identifying Your Struggles: Understanding Your Motivation and Productivity Challenges

    Introduction:

    One of the first steps in achieving your goals and changing your habits is to understand the underlying causes of your motivation and productivity challenges. Whether it's procrastination, negative thoughts and emotions, or simply a lack of motivation, understanding the root of these struggles is crucial to finding effective solutions.

    Self-Awareness and Self-Reflection:

    One of the most important tools for identifying your struggles is self-awareness and self-reflection. This involves taking the time to observe your thoughts, emotions, and behaviors, and to identify patterns and triggers that may be contributing to your struggles. For example, if you find yourself procrastinating on a regular basis, you may want to ask yourself what is causing this behavior and what you gain from it.

    Common Obstacles:

    Procrastination, negative thoughts, and emotions, and lack of motivation are some of the most common obstacles that people face when trying to change their habits and achieve their goals. To overcome these obstacles, it is important to understand the underlying causes and to develop strategies for addressing them.

    For example, procrastination is often caused by a lack of motivation, a fear of failure, or a lack of clarity about the task at hand. To overcome procrastination, it can be helpful to set clear and specific goals, to break tasks down into smaller, more manageable steps, and to reward yourself for making progress.

    Negative thoughts and emotions can also be a major obstacle to motivation and productivity. To overcome these thoughts and emotions, it can be helpful to practice mindfulness, to challenge negative thought patterns, and to develop coping strategies for dealing with difficult emotions.

    The Science Behind Motivation and Productivity:

    The psychological and neuroscientific factors that contribute to motivation and productivity are complex and multifaceted. Research has shown that motivation is influenced by a variety of factors, including our thoughts, emotions, and beliefs, as well as the way that we perceive and interact with our environment.

    One of the key concepts in understanding motivation is the idea of self-regulation, which refers to the ability to control our thoughts, emotions, and behaviors in order to achieve our goals. Research has shown that self-regulation is a key predictor of motivation and productivity, and that people who are able to regulate their thoughts and emotions are more likely to achieve their goals.

    Another important concept in understanding motivation is the idea of goal-setting, which refers to the process of setting specific and measurable objectives for oneself. Research has shown that setting specific and challenging goals is associated with higher levels of motivation and productivity, and that people who set goals for themselves are more likely to achieve them.

    Conclusion:

    In order to change your habits and achieve your goals, it is essential to understand the underlying causes of your motivation and productivity challenges. By developing self-awareness and self-reflection, identifying common obstacles, and understanding the psychological and neuroscientific factors that contribute to motivation and productivity, you can develop strategies and techniques that will help you to overcome these challenges and to achieve your goals.

    Changing Your Mindset: Overcoming Negative Thoughts and Emotions

    Overcoming negative thoughts and emotions is a crucial step in understanding and addressing motivation and productivity challenges. Negative thoughts, such as self-doubt, fear of failure, and perfectionism, can lead to procrastination, lack of motivation, and ultimately, decreased productivity.

    One effective strategy for changing your mindset is to challenge negative thoughts through cognitive-behavioral techniques such as cognitive restructuring. This involves identifying and questioning the assumptions and beliefs that underlie negative thoughts, and replacing them with more balanced and realistic perspectives.

    For example, if you find yourself thinking "I can't do this, it's too hard," you can challenge this thought by asking yourself: "What is the evidence for and against this thought? Are there other ways of looking at this situation?" This can help to shift your perspective and reduce feelings of helplessness and hopelessness.

    Another effective strategy is to practice mindfulness and acceptance. This involves learning to observe and accept negative thoughts and emotions without getting caught up in them. Mindfulness practices such as meditation and yoga can help to increase awareness and decrease reactivity to negative thoughts and emotions.

    Lastly, finding healthy ways to express and cope with negative emotions can also help to change your mindset. This can include talking to a therapist or counselor, journaling, or engaging in activities that promote emotional regulation such as art, music, or exercise.

    It's important to remember that changing your mindset and overcoming negative thoughts and emotions is not a one-time event, but rather a continuous process that requires patience, practice, and self-compassion.

    In conclusion, understanding and addressing the underlying causes of motivation and productivity challenges is key in achieving goals and reaching a sense of fulfillment. Identifying the factors that hold us back and learning effective strategies to change our mindset can lead to a more positive and productive life.

    The Quest for a perfect coffee cup using a Stovetop Espresso Machine

    Telumire 5th March 2023 at 5:14pm
    Blogcoffee

    The gear : italian coffee maker (or moka pot)

    I buyed this a while ago, and never managed to make a pallatable coffee with this. Either it was too strong, or muddy.

    It's time to do my due diligence and figure out how to use this thing right, in order to maybe, one day, craft the ellusive perfect coffee cup.

    Mistakes were made

    Too fine !
    Too fine coffe grind can overbrew. It should be a litle bit coarser than expresso.
    Packing it down
    Do not pack the grind down, or the water will not be able to permeate easily.
    Going past medium heat
    It works very similar to a siphon brew system, you're boiling the water and the vapor pressure force the water up to the chamber containing the grind, taking advantage of the Pascal's Principle
    Leaving on the burner too long
    Lead to overbrewing and bitter taste. Pale/Bubbly = done : remove the moka pot and apply cold water to stop the brewing process.
    Not cleaning the pot
    Coffee oil and mineral deposits can lead to bitter taste, so clean up your moka pot.

    Overthinking much ?

    The issue with adjusting a coffee brewing technique is the lack of reproductibility and objectivity. If we wait too long between samplings, we can forget previous samplings, and if we taste coffee samples too quickly, the tong will still be coated in the previous coffee and will not provide a reliable measurement. Palate fatigue is also a thing to take into consideration.

    Thus, to get optimal measures, we should not rely on taste. But for that, we need to establish some objective criterions affecting the quality of a coffee cup.

    • bitterness
    • acidity
    • turbidity
    • temperature
    • ?
    Measuring bitterness

    It's apparently possible to measure the bitterness of beer with an UV-Visible spectrophotometer, ant it's possible to build a Nanodrop Style UV/Vis Spectrometer at home.

    Measuring acidity

    pH test ?

    Measuring turbidity

    Turbidity meter or Turbidity tube

    References and further reading

    • Whittard of Chelsea Official : How to Make the Perfect Stovetop Espresso
    • loodog coffee : Why your Moka pot tastes bad
    • loodog coffee : Why your moka pot still sucks and Italians hate me.
    • A. VARLAMOV e G. BALESTRINO: LA FISICA DI UN BUON CAFFE
    • Concetto Gianino : Experimental analysis of the Italian coffee pot "moka"
    • Warren D King : The physics of a stove-top espresso machine
    • Experimental investigation of steam pressure coffee extraction in a stove-top coffee maker
    • Swelling properties of roasted coffee particles

    Weight loss strategies

    Telumire 25th January 2023 at 5:28am
    Different methods may work better for different people, so it's best to consult a health professional before starting any new diet or exercise programme.

    Weight loss can plateau or even stall due to the body's ability to adapt to reduced energy intake. This is known as adaptive thermogenesis, which is the reduction in metabolic rate that occurs as a result of calorie restriction. When the body is in an energy deficit, it will try to conserve energy by slowing down metabolic processes. This can make it harder for a person to continue losing weight, even if they are still following the same diet and exercise programme. In addition, as a person loses weight, their energy needs decrease, which means that the same calorie intake that once caused weight loss may no longer be enough to maintain the weight loss.

    Several strategies can be used to avoid or reduce the effects of adaptive thermogenesis:

    1. Increase Physical Activity: Increasing physical activity can help boost your metabolism and counteract the slowing of metabolic rate that can occur during weight loss.
    2. Adequate Sleep and Stress Management: Adequate sleep and stress management are also important for preventing metabolic adaptation. Sleep deprivation and chronic stress can both lead to hormonal imbalances that can slow metabolism.
    3. High-Intensity Interval Training (HIIT): High-intensity interval training is a form of exercise that alternates short bursts of intense activity with periods of rest. This type of exercise has been shown to boost metabolism and help prevent the metabolic slowdown that can occur during weight loss.
    4. Metabolic Resistance Training (MRT): MRT is a form of resistance training that utilizes short rest periods between sets, which can help boost metabolism and preserve muscle mass during weight loss.
    5. Resistance Training: Building muscle through resistance training can boost metabolism and help counteract the metabolic slowdown that occurs during weight loss.
    6. Intermittent Fasting: Intermittent fasting is a pattern of eating that alternates periods of eating with periods of fasting. It can promote weight loss by reducing overall calorie intake, and has been shown to improve insulin sensitivity, which can help to reduce the risk of obesity and related diseases.
    7. Mediterranean diet: This diet focuses on whole, unprocessed foods, such as fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and healthy fats, and has been shown to be beneficial for weight loss, as well as heart and overall health.
    8. Gradual Caloric Reduction: Instead of cutting calories abruptly, try reducing them gradually. This will give your body time to adjust and will prevent the metabolic slowdown that can occur when calories are cut too quickly.
    9. High-Protein Diets: Eating a diet high in protein can help preserve muscle mass during weight loss, which can help boost metabolism.

    The body is very adaptable, so it's important to keep challenging it with different strategies. Be patient and consistent as weight loss is a slow process and weight loss plateaus are normal. Losing weight isn't just about cutting calories, it's also about making healthier choices, such as eating nutritious foods and being active.
